export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "s5-1-1", "html": "<p>Semilocal density functional theory (DFT) reads nickel oxide — experimentally a robust antiferromagnetic insulator with a large gap — and returns a metal.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"10\">[10]</sup> The same failure renders CoO, CePO<span class=\"math\">$_4$</span>, and CeVO<span class=\"math\">$_4$</span> metallic where experiment confirms wide-gap insulators.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"151\">[151]</sup> Chapter 3 carried La<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>CuO<span class=\"math\">$_4$</span> as the emblem (taxonomy mode 1); Chapter 4 closed on superconductors, and the handoff is direct: one PRL study finds that in CoO the Hubbard interaction itself mediates an electron–phonon term nearly identical in magnitude to the conventional Kohn–Sham term for the partially filled Co 3<span class=\"math\">$d$</span> orbitals.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"152\">[152]</sup> In correlated oxides, even the lattice-coupling channel misses leading-order physics unless correlation sits inside the Hamiltonian.</p>\n<p>The device stakes are defect levels, and defect levels are what the failing methods get wrong. Superconducting-qubit coherence is limited by dielectric loss from two-level-system (TLS) defects in amorphous oxides and at interfaces.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"153\">[153]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"154\">[154]</sup> Mott insulators — VO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>, NbO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>, NiO — are the active elements of threshold-switching memristors and Mott neurons, where the device <em>is</em> the correlation-driven metal–insulator transition.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"155\">[155]</sup> Wide-gap oxide defect states are candidate single-photon emitters and spin sensors whose charge-transition levels carry the eV-scale uncertainty of case box 5.1.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"11\">[11]</sup> (Spintronics market estimates diverge ~15× across reputable 2025 reports — I rest the impact case on physics.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"156\">[156]</sup>) The class passes my Chapter 2 admission tests.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s5-2-1", "html": "<p>The root error is self-interaction: semilocal functionals over-delocalize localized <span class=\"math\">$d$</span>/<span class=\"math\">$f$</span> electrons, so mean-field DFT predicts metals where nature puts Mott and charge-transfer insulators, and understates gaps even where it gets the phase right.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"151\">[151]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"10\">[10]</sup> The failure is <em>structural</em>: mean field decouples the spin and charge correlations that constitute the insulating state, so no same-form functional repairs it. The standard patch, DFT+U, restores the insulator but imports an empirical Hubbard <span class=\"math\">$U$</span> (and Hund <span class=\"math\">$J$</span>) that depends strongly on projector and population-analysis convention and &quot;can be arbitrary and is often either fit to experiments or selected from previous literature values&quot; — the seed of this class's internal counter-narrative, developed in §5.4.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"151\">[151]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"157\">[157]</sup> Even phonons inherit it: plain DFT gives CoO a fictitious metallic ground state, leaving phonons ill-defined until Hubbard-corrected perturbation theory restores them.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"158\">[158]</sup> Multiferroics too: LDA renders BiFeO<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span> metallic, no tested standard functional opens a gap in YMnO<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span> (one meta-GGA study),<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"159\">[159]</sup> and GW/DMFT/hybrids stay &quot;far from being practical&quot; for such complex cells.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"160\">[160]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s5-2-2", "html": "<p>Even careful, minimally empirical correction leaves residuals that move device predictions; Table 5.1 collects the five load-bearing numbers.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 5.1 — Residual errors in correlated oxides and quantum materials after best-practice correction (verified as of 2026-07-17). MAE = mean absolute error; MAPE = mean absolute percentage error.</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Quantity</th>\n<th>System/benchmark</th>\n<th>Method/model</th>\n<th>Predicted</th>\n<th>Reference/experimental</th>\n<th>Error magnitude</th>\n<th>Source</th>\n<th>Confidence</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Heisenberg exchange <span class=\"math\">$J$</span></td>\n<td>NiO, prototypical Mott–Hubbard insulator</td>\n<td>DFT+U+J, linear-response <span class=\"math\">$U$</span> and <span class=\"math\">$J$</span>, minimal empiricism</td>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$J$</span> parameter set</td>\n<td>Experimental <span class=\"math\">$J$</span> values</td>\n<td>13% RMS (best case)</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"157\">[157]</sup></td>\n<td>High</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Magnetic ordering temperature <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span></td>\n<td>Magnetic-materials benchmark compilations (incl. NEMAD)</td>\n<td>DFT exchange + Monte Carlo/mean-field; ML graph networks</td>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span></td>\n<td>Measured <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span></td>\n<td>15–35% (DFT); 20–40% MAPE (ML)</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"161\">[161]</sup></td>\n<td>Medium (single compilation)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>O-vacancy formation energy <span class=\"math\">$E_f$</span></td>\n<td>ZnO</td>\n<td>HSE hybrid vs diffusion Monte Carlo (DMC)</td>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$E_f(\\mathrm{V_O})$</span></td>\n<td>DMC as reference</td>\n<td>~1 eV split; effective-<span class=\"math\">$U$</span> sign flips</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"11\">[11]</sup></td>\n<td>High</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Quasiparticle band gap</td>\n<td>NiO</td>\n<td>G<span class=\"math\">$_0$</span>W<span class=\"math\">$_0$</span>@DFT+U vs HSE/G<span class=\"math\">$_0$</span>W<span class=\"math\">$_0$</span> vs quasiparticle-self-consistent GW</td>\n<td>3.8 / 4.7 / 4.8 eV</td>\n<td>Same compound, same observable</td>\n<td>~1 eV starting-point spread</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"162\">[162]</sup></td>\n<td>High</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Band gap</td>\n<td>CdTe</td>\n<td>GGA</td>\n<td>0.68 eV</td>\n<td>~1.5 eV experimental</td>\n<td>~0.8 eV underestimate</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"163\">[163]</sup></td>\n<td>High</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>The first two rows are <em>precision</em> failures: 13% RMS is the best a low-empiricism DFT+U+J workflow achieves on the literature's most-studied Mott insulator, and since <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> scales with the exchange integrals, that floor propagates into the 15–35% <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> band — one benchmark compilation finds ML graph models no better at 20–40% MAPE, so surrogates inherit rather than fix the magnetic error.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"157\">[157]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"161\">[161]</sup> The third and fourth rows are <em>method-consistency</em> failures, and they worry me more: two beyond-semilocal methods, each defensible as &quot;accurate,&quot; disagree at ~1 eV on a defect energy and on a quasiparticle gap, so &quot;switch to a better method&quot; is not yet a complete answer.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"11\">[11]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"162\">[162]</sup> The CdTe row prices the raw semilocal error — over-delocalized Cd 4<span class=\"math\">$d$</span> states lift the valence band — that <span class=\"math\">$U$</span> or hybrid patches must absorb at costs impractical for alloy-defect screening.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"163\">[163]</sup></p>\n<div class=\"pullbox\">\n<p><strong>Case box 5.1 — Two accurate methods, 1 eV apart (the ZnO defect split).</strong> The oxygen vacancy in ZnO is the benchmark defect of a wide-gap oxide: it controls <span class=\"math\">$n$</span>-type doping, color centers, and candidate quantum-emitter behavior. Santana and co-workers computed its formation energy with diffusion Monte Carlo (DMC) against the HSE screened hybrid — two methods a practitioner would each call &quot;accurate.&quot; The DMC formation energy comes out <em>about 1 eV higher</em> than HSE's; DMC's ZnO gap of 3.43(9) eV and its vacancy transition levels (deep, 1.8–2.5 eV above the valence-band maximum) reorder the defect physics; and the effective <span class=\"math\">$U$</span> of the Zn 3<span class=\"math\">$d$</span> states flips <em>sign</em> — positive in DMC, negative in HSE.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"11\">[11]</sup> The lesson generalizes: defect databases built on one functional inherit its signature error, and where semilocal DFT fails qualitatively the beyond-DFT retreat options disagree at the eV scale — an eV of method noise deciding which qubit or emitter candidate looks buildable.</p>\n</div>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s5-2-3", "html": "<p>The numerically exact DMFT impurity solvers (CT-QMC and relatives) fail as screening tools on three stated counts: the fermionic sign problem — worst for multi-band systems with off-diagonal (spin–orbit) hybridization — slow half-order Monte Carlo convergence, and cost scaling as <span class=\"math\">$O(T^{-3})$</span>, blocking the low temperatures where magnetism and superconductivity live.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"164\">[164]</sup> The average sign decays as <span class=\"math\">$\\langle \\mathrm{sign} \\rangle \\sim e^{-\\beta \\Delta F}$</span>; a 2026 preprint attacking this bottleneck for high-throughput screening confirms it is seen as <em>the</em> blocker.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"165\">[165]</sup> GW sits on the same wall from the other side: G<span class=\"math\">$_0$</span>W<span class=\"math\">$_0$</span> is strongly starting-point-dependent,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"166\">[166]</sup> cross-code gaps deviate 0.1–0.3 eV between pseudopotential and all-electron implementations, and self-consistent GW is limited to ~10–12 atoms per cell.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"163\">[163]</sup> No current method is both qualitatively correct here and cheap enough to screen — the cost wall is scoreboard Row 10 wearing an oxide coat.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s5-2-4", "html": "<p>Topological invariants are decided by meV-scale band inversions in narrow-gap materials, so gap error becomes <em>binary</em>: PBE-level gaps plus spin–orbit coupling can manufacture an unphysical inversion — a false-positive topological-insulator prediction — while the GW that would settle it is impractical even for bulk Bi<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>Se<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>/Bi<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>Te<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"167\">[167]</sup> A single authoritative census finds roughly 60% of 130 magnetic topological materials have topologies sensitive to the interaction <span class=\"math\">$U$</span> — the label flips inside the parameter's own uncertainty; the expanded database flags 250 of 522 magnetic structures (47.9%) as nontrivial, again versus <span class=\"math\">$U$</span>.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"168\">[168]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"169\">[169]</sup> ML surrogates amplify throughput, not reliability: the JARVIS spin-orbit-spillage classifier reaches ROC AUC ≈ 0.97, but against PBE labels under fixed-<span class=\"math\">$U$</span> conventions,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"170\">[170]</sup> and a deep-generative pipeline's 62.5% hit rate is still a rate against the same labels.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"171\">[171]</sup> Catalogue size is not a proxy for usable materials.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s5-2-5", "html": "<p>Scalar-energy MLIPs have no electronic degrees of freedom: an E(3)-equivariant graph potential, however large, &quot;cannot deal with spin.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"100\">[100]</sup> The frontier is purpose-built: magnetic-MACE's self-consistent magnetic-moment loops reproduce magnetocrystalline anisotropy energy, Bain-transformation energetics, and Curie temperatures;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"172\">[172]</sup> mMTP fits explicitly to <em>magnetic forces</em>;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"173\">[173]</sup> SpinGNN++ reaches sub-meV accuracy on spin-lattice Hamiltonians and predicted a previously unknown ferrimagnetic ground state for monolayer CrTe<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"100\">[100]</sup> All train on spin-polarized DFT or DFT+U labels, so their ceiling is the §5.2.1–5.2.2 error stack, not experiment: exchange-predicting networks lean on collinear DFT plus force-theorem mappings, omit spin–orbit coupling, and interpolate the same ~13%-class <span class=\"math\">$J$</span> errors.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"174\">[174]</sup> None discover Mott physics from scratch.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s5-3", "html": "<p>Scoreboard Rows 9 and 10 bind this class, and both sit at readiness L — frontier — which is where discovery value concentrates. Three levers look real. <strong>Spin- and electronic-DOF models exist and are adoptable.</strong> The Row 9 toolkit spans sub-meV spin-lattice potentials,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"100\">[100]</sup> foundation models taking spin and charge as explicit inputs (UMA's omol head),<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"101\">[101]</sup> and the magnetic-MACE/mMTP lineage;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"172\">[172]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"173\">[173]</sup> my move is adoption, not rebuilding — these capture <em>given</em> magnetic states, enough to simulate Mott-device operating points once the states are anchored. <strong>ML-DMFT attacks the cost wall.</strong> Neural-network impurity solvers amortize across impurity parameter space instead of treating each solve as new,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"140\">[140]</sup> and DMFT-initialization schemes aim to shrink the sign's exponential decay for screening workflows.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"165\">[165]</sup> <strong>The reference layer is moving but unproven on solids.</strong> ML exchange-correlation functionals now beat hybrids on molecular benchmarks — Skala at 2.8 kcal/mol (≈0.12 eV) on GMTKN55 at semi-local cost — but DM21 demonstrably fails transition-metal chemistry, so Row 10's ceiling over correlated oxides stands as of 2026-07-17.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"104\">[104]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"103\">[103]</sup> Until it moves, experiment-anchored correction is the honest bridge: these errors are systematic, so a few measured anchors — neutron-derived <span class=\"math\">$J$</span>, <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span>, spectroscopic gap — can pin the empirical-<span class=\"math\">$U$</span> subspace for a target chemistry at GPU-day cost, converting §5.2.2's residuals into bounded, publishable error bars.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s5-4", "html": "<p>The strongest counter-narrative here comes from inside the standard method. DFT+U &quot;predictions&quot; can be retrofits: <span class=\"math\">$U$</span> is frequently fit to experiment or inherited from prior literature,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"151\">[151]</sup> first-principles <span class=\"math\">$U$</span> and <span class=\"math\">$J$</span> shift with population-analysis convention,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"157\">[157]</sup> and different defensible <span class=\"math\">$U$</span> values deliver different gaps, couplings, and — for ~60% of magnetic topological candidates — different topology.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"168\">[168]</sup> Mixing DFT for the elemental reference with DFT+U for the oxide quietly contaminates formation energies: one LaFeO<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span> study finds bcc iron's lattice parameter at 3.03 Å with <span class=\"math\">$U_\\mathrm{Fe} = 7$</span> eV versus 2.83 Å without <span class=\"math\">$U$</span>, against 2.87 Å measured.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"175\">[175]</sup> DMFT has its own version: for NdNiO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>, conclusions on magnetism and the insulating phase depend on how the correlated subspace is built.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"176\">[176]</sup> A pipeline cannot even assume correlation strength: CoSn needs DFT bands renormalized ~1.5× to match ARPES while CsV<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>Sb<span class=\"math\">$_5$</span> matches DFT as weakly correlated.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"177\">[177]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"178\">[178]</sup> The class's flagship applications carry their own credibility debt — the retracted Majorana-conductance claims and Nature's &quot;reproducibility crisis&quot; editorial,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"179\">[179]</sup> the retracted room-temperature-superconductivity papers, and LK-99's collapse into a Cu<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>S artifact<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"180\">[180]</sup> — so I hold every claim here, mine included, to prospective validation. This is the longest-horizon bet in my portfolio; the <span class=\"math\">$U$</span>-arbitrariness is why the horizon is long.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s5-5", "html": "<p>Both governments fund this class's destination; neither program fixes its theory. China's 15th Five-Year Plan, adopted 2026-03-11, places quantum technology at the top of seven designated &quot;future industries,&quot; backed by roughly <span class=\"math\">$17.5B (RMB 121.8B) in three regional quantum venture funds — plan facts official; the fund figure is single-analyst, scale-only.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"181\">[181]</sup> The United States reauthorized the National Quantum Initiative in December 2024 at ~$</span>2.7B for FY2025–29,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"49\">[49]</sup> stood up a DOE Office of Artificial Intelligence and Quantum in the 2025-11-20 reorganization ($1.2B FY2027 request),<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"60\">[60]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"182\">[182]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"183\">[183]</sup> and gave NSF's X-Labs instrument for independent research organizations a Quantum Systems topic among its first two, proposals due 2026-07-24.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"184\">[184]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"185\">[185]</sup> The symmetry is plain: both programs buy experiments, qubits, and compute; neither buys a screening-capable correlated-electron method, because none is for sale.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s5-6", "html": "<p>Chain 9 in my roadmap runs: correlation-aware MLIPs — spin- and electronic-DOF potentials anchored to experiment — to Mott and correlated-oxide devices, to neuromorphic and memory hardware, to roughly 100× more energy-efficient AI compute. I put capability before discovery here: this is the one class where I refuse to name a target material until the method earns it. My first milestone is an experiment-anchored exchange-and-defect capability on a small oxide set — <span class=\"math\">$J$</span> errors bounded against neutron data, defect levels cross-checked HSE-versus-DMC where both exist, every prediction published with its error bar — executed prospectively, so Chapter 3's skeptic register has nothing to work with. Only after that capability survives outside scrutiny does the chain's device end become a claim rather than a direction.</p>\n" },
]
